<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-exp-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Exponential Functions</title>

  <p> 
    <definition xml:id="def-exp-function">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An <term>exponential function</term> is a function that can be written in the form
          <md>
            f(x) = a^x
          </md>
          where <m>a</m> is a positive number (not equal to 1) called the <term>base</term> of the function.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </p>

  <p>
    The behavior of the function depends on the value of the base, <m>a</m>. For example, if <m>a=2</m>, the graph
    <m>y = 2^x</m> looks like

    <figure>
      <caption>Graph of exponential growth</caption>
        <image width="60%">
          <prefigure label="prefigure-exp-growth" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
            <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
              <definition>
              f(x) = 2^x
              </definition>
              <coordinates bbox="[-5,-5,5,35]">
              <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
              <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
              </coordinates>
            </diagram>
          </prefigure>
        </image>
    </figure>
  </p>

  <p>
    We can see several properties of the function <m>y=2^x</m> from its graph. It's domain is <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.
    This is because, no matter what we choose for the value of <m>x</m>, the expression <m>2^x</m> is always defined.
    The graph's range does not contain any negative numbers. In fact, <m>y=0</m> is an asymptote of the graph, and the
    range is <m>(0, \infty)</m>. The graph does not have any <m>x</m>-intercepts, reflecting the fact that the
    equation <m>2^x = 0</m> does not have any solutions. The graph has a <m>y</m>-intercept at <m>y=1</m>, because
    <m>f(0) = 2^0 = 1</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    When we consider the end behavior of the graph, we can see that as <m>x</m> moves to the left on the graph,
    the <m>y</m>-values get closer to the horizontal asymptote. We can write this concisely as
    <md>
      <mrow>y \rightarrow 0 ~\text{as}~ x \rightarrow -\infty.</mrow>
    </md>
    On the other side, we can see that as <m>x</m> moves to the right on the graph, the <m>y</m>-values get
    larger and larger. So we can write
    <md>
      <mrow>y \rightarrow \infty ~\text{as}~ x \rightarrow \infty.</mrow>
    </md>
    In fact, as <m>x</m> moves to the right, the <m>y</m>-values are growing extremely quickly. Consider this table
    of values.

  <table>
  <tabular top="medium">
    <row bottom="medium" left="medium">
      <cell right="medium">x</cell>
      <cell right="medium">0</cell>
      <cell right="medium">1</cell>
      <cell right="medium">2</cell>
      <cell right="medium">3</cell>
      <cell right="medium">4</cell>
      <cell right="medium">5</cell>
    </row>
    <row bottom="medium" left="medium">
      <cell right="medium">y</cell>
      <cell right="medium">1</cell>
      <cell right="medium">2</cell>
      <cell right="medium">4</cell>
      <cell right="medium">8</cell>
      <cell right="medium">16</cell>
      <cell right="medium">32</cell>
    </row>
    </tabular>
    </table>
    Notice that for each step when the <m>x</m>-value increases by one, the <m>y</m>-value doubles. This doubling
    quickly leads to very large <m>y</m>-values. For example, if we continued our table a few more steps to 
    <m>x=10</m>, the corresponding <m>y</m>-value would be <m>f(10) = 2^10 = 1024</m>. This type of rapid growth occurs
    whenever the base of the exponential function is greater than 1, and is called <term>exponential growth</term>.
  </p>

</section>